'''B<U+00E9>la the Blind''' ({{lang-hu|Vak B<U+00E9>la}}; {{lang-hr|Bela Slijepi}}; {{lang-sk|Belo Slep<U+00FD>}}; {{circa}} 1109&nbsp;<U+2013> 13 February 1141) was [[King of Hungary]] and [[King of Croatia|Croatia]] from 1131. He was blinded along with his rebellious father [[<U+00C1>lmos, Duke of Croatia|<U+00C1>lmos]] on the order of <U+00C1>lmos's brother, King [[Coloman of Hungary]]. B<U+00E9>la grew up in monasteries during the reign of Coloman's son [[Stephen II of Hungary|Stephen II]]. The childless king arranged B<U+00E9>la's marriage with [[Helena of Rascia]], who would become her husband's co-ruler throughout his reign.

B<U+00E9>la was crowned king at least two months after the death of Stephen II, implying that his accession to the throne did not happen without opposition. Two violent purges were carried out among the partisans of his predecessors to strengthen B<U+00E9>la's rule. King Coloman's alleged son [[Boris Kalamanos|Boris]] tried to dethrone B<U+00E9>la but the king and his allies defeated the pretender's troops in 1132. In the second half of B<U+00E9>la's reign, Hungary adopted an active foreign policy. [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]] and [[Split, Croatia|Split]] seem to have accepted B<U+00E9>la's suzerainty around 1136.

==Early years until 1131==
[[File:<U+00C1>lmos herceg.jpg|thumb |right |190px |alt=<U+00C1>lmos and B<U+00E9>la are blinded | The child B<U+00E9>la and his father, [[<U+00C1>lmos, Duke of Croatia|<U+00C1>lmos]] are blinded on King [[Coloman of Hungary|Coloman]]'s order (from the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'')]]

B<U+00E9>la was the only son of Duke [[<U+00C1>lmos, Duke of Croatia|<U+00C1>lmos]]{{mdash}}the younger brother of King [[Coloman of Hungary]]{{mdash}}by his wife, Predslava of Kiev.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=Appendix 3}} Historians Gyula Krist<U+00F3> and Ferenc Makk write that B<U+00E9>la was born between 1108 and 1110.{{sfn|Makk|1994|p=90}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=161}}
<U+00C1>lmos devised several plots to dethrone his brother.{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=518}} In retaliation, the king deprived <U+00C1>lmos of his ''[[Duchy (Kingdom of Hungary)|ducatus]]'' or "duchy" between 1105 and 1108.{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=28}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=145<U+2013>146}} <U+00C1>lmos did not give up his ambitions and King Coloman had him and the child B<U+00E9>la blinded between 1112 and 1115 to secure a peaceful succession for his own son, [[Stephen II of Hungary|Stephen]].{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=234}}{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=518}} According to one of the two versions of these events recorded in the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'', the king even ordered that B<U+00E9>la should be castrated but the soldier who was charged with this task refused to execute the order.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=161}}{{sfn|Cartledge|2011|p=518}}

[[File:Pr<U+00E9>posts<U+00E1>gi romok ThT.JPG|thumb|left |190px|alt=D<U+00F6>m<U+00F6>s monastery | Ruins of the monastery at [[D<U+00F6>m<U+00F6>s]]]]
[[File:P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad - Benc<U+00E9>s ap<U+00E1>ts<U+00E1>g.jpg|thumb|left |190px |alt=P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad Abbey | Ruins of the [[Benedictine]] [[P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad Abbey]]]]

{{Quote|[The] King took the Duke and his infant son Bela and blinded them. He also gave orders that the infant Bela should be castrated. But the man who was instructed to blind them feared God and the sterility of the royal line, and therefore he castrated a dog and brought its testicles to the King.|''[[Illuminated Chronicle|The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle]]''<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 150.106), p. 133.</ref>}}

After their blinding, <U+00C1>lmos lived in the monastery of [[D<U+00F6>m<U+00F6>s]], which he had founded.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=161}} Krist<U+00F3> and Makk write that it is probable that B<U+00E9>la lived with his father in the monastery.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=161}}{{sfn|Makk|1994|p=90}} The ''[[Annales Posonienses]]'' relates that "the child was growing in the reign of King Coloman's son, Stephen", who ascended the throne in 1116.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=163}} Having hatched a failed plot against the king, <U+00C1>lmos left the monastery and fled to [[Constantinople]] in about 1125.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=49}} For unknown reasons, B<U+00E9>la did not follow his father to the [[Byzantine Empire]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}} The ''Illuminated Chronicle'' narrates that he was kept "concealed in Hungary from the fury"<ref name="Chronicon_157_112_135">''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 157.112), p. 135.</ref> of the king.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}} B<U+00E9>la settled in the [[P<U+00E9>csv<U+00E1>rad Abbey]], whose abbot sheltered him in secret.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}}

<U+00C1>lmos died in exile on 1 September 1127.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=24}} According to the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', B<U+00E9>la's partisans "revealed to the King, who believed him to have died after his blinding, that B<U+00E9>la was alive".<ref name="Chronicon_157_112_135"/>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}} On hearing this, King Stephen II "rejoiced with great joy, for he knew beyond doubt that he would have no heir".<ref name="Chronicon_157_112_135"/>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}} The king even arranged B<U+00E9>la's marriage with Helena of Rascia and granted [[Tolna, Hungary|Tolna]] to the couple around 1129.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=165}}{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=29}} King Stephen II died in early 1131.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=29}} A late source{{mdash}}the [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] chronicle known as ''Tarih-i <U+00DC>ng<U+00FC>r<U+00FC>s'' or ''The History of the Hungarians''{{mdash}}narrates that B<U+00E9>la ascended the throne after his predecessor's nephew, [[Saul of Hungary|Saul]] whom Stephen II had nominated as his heir had died.{{sfn|Makk|1989|pp=29, 135, 182}} B<U+00E9>la II was crowned in [[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]] on 28 April, substantiating the reliability of this report.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}} However, no scholarly consensus on the exact circumstances of B<U+00E9>la's ascension exists. According to Gyula Krist<U+00F3>, B<U+00E9>la was crowned after a civil war between his and Saul's partisans, but P<U+00E1>l Engel does not mention any conflict related to B<U+00E9>la's succession.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=164}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}}
{{clear}}

==Reign==

===Consolidation (1131<U+2013>1132)===
[[File:Chronicon Pictum P113 Az aradi v<U+00E9>res gy<U+0171>l<U+00E9>s.JPG|thumb |upright |alt=Assembly at Arad | Massacre of B<U+00E9>la II's opponents on the orders of Queen [[Helena of Rascia|Helena]] at the assembly of [[Arad, Romania|Arad]] in 1131]]

B<U+00E9>la's blindness prevented him from administering his kingdom without assistance.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}}{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=236}} He put his trust in his wife and her brother [[Belo<U+0161> Vukanovi<U+0107>|Belo<U+0161>]].{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=236}} Both royal and private charters from B<U+00E9>la's reign emphasize Queen Helena's pre-eminent role in the decision-making process, proving that the king regarded his wife as his co-ruler.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=166<U+2013>167}} According to the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', at "an assembly of the realm near [[Arad, Romania|Arad]]"<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 160.114), p. 136.</ref> in early to mid-1131, Queen Helena ordered the slaughter of all noblemen who were accused of having suggested the blinding of her husband to King Coloman.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}}{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=31}} B<U+00E9>la distributed the goods of the executed magnates between the newly established [[Arad Chapter]] and the early 11th-century [[<U+00D3>buda Chapter]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=171}}

B<U+00E9>la's was on good terms with the [[Holy Roman Empire]], jeopardizing the interests of [[Boleslaw III of Poland]] who had been warring with the empire.{{sfn|Manteuffel|1982|p=115}} The Polish monarch decided to support a pretender to the Hungarian crown named [[Boris Kalamanos|Boris]].{{sfn|Manteuffel|1982|p=115}} Boris was born to King Coloman's second wife [[Euphemia of Kiev]] after his mother was repudiated for adultery.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}} After Boris arrived in Poland, a number of Hungarian noblemen joined him.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=32}} Others sent messengers to Boris "to invite him that he should come and with their help claim the kingdom for himself",<ref name="Chronicon_161_115_136">''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 161.115), p. 136.</ref> according to the ''Illuminated Chronicle''.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=172}}{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=32}}

Accompanied by Polish and [[Kievan Rus'|Rus']] reinforcements, Boris broke into Hungary in mid-1132.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=32}} B<U+00E9>la entered into an alliance with [[Leopold III, Margrave of Austria]].{{sfn|Makk|1989|pp=32<U+2013>33}} Before launching a counter-attack against Boris, B<U+00E9>la convoked a council on the river [[Saj<U+00F3>]].{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=32}} The ''Illuminated Chronicle'' relates that the King asked "the eminent men of Hungary" who were present if they knew whether Boris "was a bastard or the son of King Coloman".<ref name="Chronicon_161_115_136"/>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=168}} The King's partisans attacked and murdered all those who proved to be "disloyal and divided in their minds"<ref name="Chronicon_161_115_136"/> during the meeting.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=169}} Boris, who thought that the majority of the Hungarian lords supported his claim, in vain sent one of his partisans to B<U+00E9>la's camp to incite the King's retinue to mutiny.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=169}}
 
{{Quote|[Samson] proposed to go to the assembly of the King and there openly and publicly insult him. All approved and [Boris] himself, misled by empty hope, gave him great thanks; for he wanted to complete what he had begun, and he thought that after the King had been thus insulted the kingdom would be his. The King had taken up his station near the river [Saj<U+00F3>], and as he sat in his tent with his nobles and soldiers, behold, [Samson] entered and said to the King: "Vile dog, what are you doing with the kingdom? It is better that your lord [Boris] have the kingdom and for your to live in your monastery, as your father did." There was commotion among the nobles of the realm, and Johannes, the son of Otto, the King's notary&nbsp;... , said to Count Bud: "Why are we waiting? Why do we not seize him?" As they made to seize him, he hastily leapt upon a horse and fled.|''[[Illuminated Chronicle|The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle]]''<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 161.115<U+2013>116), pp.&nbsp;136<U+2013>137.</ref>}}

B<U+00E9>la tried to persuade the Polish monarch to stop supporting the pretender.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=169<U+2013>170}} However, Boleslaw remained loyal to Boris.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=170}} In the decisive battle, which was fought on the river Saj<U+00F3> on 22 July 1132, the Hungarian and Austrian troops defeated Boris and his allies.{{sfn|Manteuffel|1982|p=115}}{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=33}}

===Expansion (1132<U+2013>1139)===

Boleslaw III of Poland could not assist Boris after the [[Battle of the Saj<U+00F3>]].{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=33}} B<U+00E9>la's allies{{mdash}}[[Sob<U+011B>slav I, Duke of Bohemia|Sob<U+011B>slav I of Bohemia]] and [[Volodymyrko Volodarovych|Volodimirko of Peremyshl]]{{mdash}}invaded Poland each year between 1132 and 1135.{{sfn|Manteuffel|1982|p=115}}{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=33}} Sob<U+011B>slav regularly{{mdash}}in 1133, 1134, 1137, and 1139{{mdash}}visited B<U+00E9>la's court.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=35}} The Czech monarch even persuaded [[Lothar III, Holy Roman Emperor]] to force Boleslaw III to abandon Boris and recognize B<U+00E9>la's rule in Hungary in August 1135.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=33}}{{sfn|Manteuffel|1982|p=116}}

[[File:Bela2 pecet.jpg|thumb |left |190px |alt=B<U+00E9>la's seal | The seal of B<U+00E9>la II]]

Hungary adopted an expansionist policy after Boris's attempts to dethrone B<U+00E9>la.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=35}} The chronicler [[Thomas the Archdeacon]] relates that [[Gaudius]], who became [[Archbishop of Split]] in 1136, "enjoyed great favor with the kings of Hungary" and "often visited their court".<ref>''Archdeacon Thomas of Split: History of the Bishops of Salona and Split'' (ch. 19.), p. 105.</ref>{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|p=227}} The report suggests that Split accepted B<U+00E9>la II's suzerainty around 1136, but this interpretation of the sources is not universally accepted by historians.{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|p=227}}{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=35}} The exact circumstances surrounding the submission of Bosnia are unknown but the region seems to have accepted B<U+00E9>la's suzerainty without resistance by 1137.{{sfn|Makk|1989|pp=33, 136}} Historian [[John V. A. Fine]] writes that the northeastern regions of the province formed part of Queen Helena's dowry.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=236}} The Hungarian army penetrated into the valley of the [[Rama (Neretva)|Rama River]], a tributary of the [[Neretva River]], in about 1137.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=33}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}} Although B<U+00E9>la assumed the title [[King of Rama]] in token of the new conquest, the permanent occupation of the region is not proven.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}}

Hungarian troops participated in a campaign launched by Grand Prince [[Yaropolk II of Kiev]] against [[Vsevolod II of Kiev|Vsevolod of Kiev]] in 1139.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=35}}{{sfn|Dimnik|1994|p=344}} B<U+00E9>la strengthened his alliance with the Holy Roman Empire.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=35}} For this purpose, he gave financial support to [[Otto of Bamberg]]'s missions among the [[Pomeranians (Slavic tribe)|Pomeranians]] and arranged the engagement of his daughter [[Sophia of Hungary (nun)|Sophia]] with [[Henry Berengar|Henry]], son of the new German king [[Conrad III of Germany|Conrad III]] in June 1139.{{sfn|Makk|1989|p=35}}

===Last years (1139<U+2013>1141)===
[[File:Denar Bela2.jpg|thumb |right |alt=B<U+00E9>la's denar | B<U+00E9>la's denar]]
According to the Hungarian chronicles, in the last few years of his life B<U+00E9>la became a drunkard.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}} His courtiers took advantage of his drunkenness to receive grants from him.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=174}} When he was in an alcoholic stupor, he sometimes ordered the execution of innocent men.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=174}} B<U+00E9>la died on 13 February 1141, "on the [[Ides (calendar)|Ides of February]], a Thursday".<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 163.117), p. 137.</ref>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=174}} He was buried in the [[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r Basilica|Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r Cathedral]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=174}}

{{Quote|After King Bela had been established in his rule of the kingdom, he indulged himself much with wine. His courtiers found that whatever they asked of the King in his drunkenness he would grant, and after his drunkenness he could not take it back. In his drunkenness he delivered Poch and Saul, who were in [[Holy orders|religious orders]], into the hands of their enemies, and they were killed without cause.|''[[Illuminated Chronicle|The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle]]''<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 162.117), p. 137.</ref>}}

